	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Places like this should be a meeting of minds, not a mosh pit, brother. I'm here to learn and to help, not to get bashed. <br><br>Okay, its great to be able to kite (and I never said its not good to kite like you implied) but grouping is fun and like you, i was misinformed by posts. I read "soloing is the only way to go," which is just isnt so at my level. Thats what the whole post is about really. When I started my druid I read "Solo!", "Kiting!", "SOLOING RULZ!" and was taken in. I found out that although we are effective soloists we are also good in a group. <br><br>Alright, enough of defense and back to the point of this board- This has been posted here and elsewhere before, but it deserves a repost (as my above fan so surely proves)<br><br>about EXP<br><br>Exp is given by mobs is calculated thusly-&nbsp;&nbsp;  (mob lvl)*(mob lvl) *X , Where X equals category of mob, either outdoor lvl:7+(X=75), dungeon lvl:any(80), low lvl:5-6(100), newbie lvl:1-4(X varies)<br><br>To calculate exp need to complete lvl X apply this formula  X=X*X*X**C*R*L<br><br>X is the lvl<br><br>R is the racial value(Bar105, DE100, Dwarf100,   <br>  Erudite100, Gnome100, 1/2elf100, Halfling95, <br>  highelf100, human100, ogre115, troll120, Welf100<br><br>C is class value bard paladin ranger sk=14,       <br>  cleric druid shaman=10, Wiz mag enc nec=11, <br>  monk=12, rogue=9.05<br><br>L is level value, this is the one that creates <br>  hell lvls    Lvls 1-29= 1.0, Lvls 30-34:1.1 <br>  Lvls 35-39= 1.2, Lvls 40-44= 1.3, Lvls 45-50=1.4<br>  <br>If you work some formulas you'll see that the first hell level (30) requires an exponential amount of exp to complete, its spposed ly the worst hell lvl.<br><br>I hope this is enlightening and i hope i got everything righ. This is copied stolen from some theif who stole it from Giddygonzalas on some cleric board I think.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
