<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=9726011291389></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9726011291389><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=9726011291389>Soloing from levels 1 to 60</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=9726011291389#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Oct 26th 6:58 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>&#65279;I played my druid before Kunark came out, so I have not included any Kunark zones for this<br>level guide.&nbsp;&nbsp;Grouping is great, but for those times where you don't want to group, here is how I did it.  I am currently a level 51 druid.<br>Levels 1-5: Qeynos Nerbie zone, or the newbie section of Qeynos hills which is the first part of<br>the zone you come to after you zone from the North Qeynos area.  Mobs here are more often<br>around 3-4 rather than 1-2.  Don&#8217;t forget to trade in gnoll fangs to Captain Tillin in the area, and<br>the moonstones you get from him to the barkeep where Trumpy Irontoe hangs about.  Excellent<br>Xp there.  You can get a free 10-slot box from some tax collector in the second story of a house<br>near the bard guild. Check out this site for info on that.<br>Levels 6-7: By Blackburrow there are 2 spawns that have 3 gnoll watchers spawning.  This is<br>soloable with A) a good weapon and damage shield B) harmony .  There are also 2 gnolls that<br>spawn independantly to the sides of the entrance to BB.<br>Levels 7-11: Inside BB there is a snake ledge.  Group with one other from 7-9, and solo until 11.<br>Practice your conjuration dd (whirling wind I think) so that you won&#8217;t have to summon food<br>forever when you get your new dot at level 14.<br>Levels 9-14: If you want, you may head to wisp island anytime after you hit level 9.  You can<br>solo the even and yellow wisps there fairly safely, as long as your weapon is RTS or better.<br>Don&#8217;t forget the damage shield. If there is a shortage of wisps, solo the giant bats and snakes<br>there.  The snakes are the same as the ones in BB, except they have a small poison dot.  Watch<br>out for the madmen, and save up the Lightstones and GLS for the quest at the gypsy camp in NK<br>for good xp and tons of money.<br>Levels 14-19: Head to EK and solo gnolls.  Kite them a bit, and then melee the rest of the fight<br>with a damage shield.  After each fight, I was usually down 2 bars of health and 2 bars of mana. <br>At night, when the undead gnolls come out, I would solo spirit stalkers and lions, or group.<br>Levels 19-21: Do aviaks (SK and Lake Rathe), or kite and solo the level 19-21 crag spiders in<br>EK.  The spiders are great xp, and the sacs and silk (get a small sewing kit for a few gold to<br>combine silks and sell each for 1pp.)  Make you a lot of money.  If you go oom, do NOT melee. <br>Run a bit away and med.  The spiders hit for a lot, but are really slow, especially when snared.<br>Levels 21- 29: Solo Giant Skels in Rathe Mountains. They range from 22 or so to about 28, but I<br>found that kiting them was the same whether they were red or not.  They have about 750 hp, and<br>are great xp, but bad loot.  You can still do aviaks, or group for cycs and Hill giants there too.<br>Levels 25-34: If you tire of Rathe Mountains, head over to the fairy camp in Lesser Fay.  It is<br>only soloable by druids, as you must harmonize Gearheart (located in middle of camp) and 2 of<br>the 4 fairies on the perimiter.  You should be indifferent at first, so scout the place out.  They cat<br>minor spells, but the zone to MM is close by.  This is a great way to get through hell at 30.  With<br>the fear animal spell and dots, you can solo any griffons in NK, as they will be feared and dotted. <br>Watch out for Grimfeather, and keep the eyes to do the crafted arms quest.<br>34-48: You can do dwarves in BB, solo Hg&#8217;s and/or griffons in NK.  If you go oom, run and med<br>a bit.  Soloing takes a while, and is not too fun here, but when grouping gets frustrating, this is<br>great, reliable, safe xp.  Good money too.  For dwarves, when you get your 44 dot, root dot and<br>med.  Each dwarf should take about 1-2 bars of mana with the root, dot med method.<br>Levels 49 +: Grouping is best here, especially in Kunark.  If you absolutely have to solo though,<br>you can solo the level 40 (about) ice giants in Everfrost, outside the zone to perma.  Don&#8217;t get<br>too close and you can pull only one.  Once again, either root, dot and med, or kite and sit when<br>you need mana.  By 51 you shouldn&#8217;t go oom doing them.<br> <br>PS- If you ever go in a group of two with a tank, you don&#8217;t have to heal while they get beat on. <br>Dot the mob, and as it aggros you, let the tank beat on it from behind while you take baby steps<br>away from the mob.  You won&#8217;t get to med, but you won&#8217;t have to heal the tank either.  Redot or<br>dd the mob when it turns on your tank.<br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
