	   <tr><td colspan=2>hmm, correct me if I am wrong.. <br>but what you are describing is not kiting. <br>What you are describing is "root-bombing"<br>"root-bombing" is a particularly effective WIZARD solo method. The reason for this is because Wizards can cause enough damage to kill something *before* it breaks root/snare. Druids dont have the firepower wizards do so you would never succeed. "Kiting" as the name implies, involves movement, which is why the druid shines so much. The druid works best in wide open places. When you kite, you can root (or not, totally optional), cast a DoT, and then do what druids do best! RUN!. By casting SoW on yourself, you can outrun a creature while it chases you and takes damage. When the DoT runs out, stop long enough to recast and run again! This is kiting, or at least one method of kiting. Until you get SoW, however, you will be restricted to using inferior DD spells and meleeing a lot. Get a good club! :) I hope this helps. At level 15, my druid was in North Karana, kiting elephants that were conning red to me. The important thing to remember with kiting is that it works best in wide open spaces, with (for the most part) non-casting, low resistance, melee mobs. So, a shadowed man or a centaur archer would not work. :) Aviaks are extrmely popular for kiting. :) finally, if you need money.. my advice : go to Lavastorm. the risk vs reward ratio is SO off balance in the player's favor. low green mobs dropping 6 golds at a time. :) its insane! And golds add up REAL fast. :) Plus the loot you find on these creatures sells for several golds as well. I saved up 80 plats in just under 4 hours hunting here consistently. Mana? bah! just club fire drakes and save the mana for the occasional fire sprite. :) <br><br>Nahualli<br>Conjurer of the 20th Summon<br><br>Kinerian<br>Druid of the 22nd Season<br><br>Maliga<br>Shaman of the 7th Ritual<br><br>Ieran <br>Wizard of the 5th Evocation<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
